I noticed in the above summary that Glucose, BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, and BMI all have a minimum value of 0. I am going to create models using a complete dataset (using only samples where there is a measurement >0 for all variables except Prenancies) and therefore I will remove the relevant rows where these variables = 0.

# Review counts of rows where data = 0 
# (except for Pregnancies, DiabetesPedigreeFunction, & Outcome)
sapply(diabetes[,2:7], function(x) sum(x==0))

diabetes[diabetes==0] <- NA
diabetes$Pregnancies <- ifelse(is.na(diabetes$Pregnancies),0,diabetes$Pregnancies)

EDA Notes:

  • I removed incomplete cases (where values = 0 on variables besides pregnancies and Outcome).
  • The outcome variable is binary and therefore can be used in a classification model.
  • There are no missing values (NA) in the dataset.
  • All columns are type = double, no transformations are required.
  • BMI & SkinThickness are the most strongly correlated out of all variables at 0.66. I may need to exclude one of these variables from the model to avoid the issue of collinearity, which decreases model accuracy. Another pair that is highly correlated is Insulin & Glucose. However, I will most likely keep them in the model because if I leave one out, the effect may be underestimated, especially if there are unknown interaction effects between these variables.
  • The rest of the variables, in terms of their correlation, are not concerning to me.

Define Models

Build a simple model for linear classification based on the “Outcome” column.

# Set seed
set.seed(1)

# Split the data into training/test sets
train <- sample(1:nrow(diabetes), nrow(diabetes)/2)
diabetes.train <- diabetes[train,]
diabetes.test <- diabetes[-train,]

I decided to split the training and test sets into two equal groups, in terms of sample size.

Model #1: Logistic Regression

Fit the Model

I am first going to fit a model using a logistic regression (GLM) method because Outcome is a binary response variable. I decided to use all of the variables for this first model, but I may try to remove either Age or Pregnancies and see if that improves model accuracy in a future version of this analysis.

# Fit the model using training data 
diabetes.glm <- glm(Outcome ~ ., data = diabetes, family = "binomial",
                    subset = train)

# Look at summary 
summary(diabetes.glm)

Evaluate Model

# Predict the new model using the validation set
diabetes.pr <- predict(diabetes.glm, newdata = diabetes.test, 
                           type = "response")

# Assign predicted responses to 0
diabetes.glm.pr <- rep(0, length(diabetes.pr))

# Assign 1 to predicted responses if the posterior probability is >= 0.5
diabetes.glm.pr[diabetes.pr >= 0.5] <- 1

# Compute the validation set error
glm.testerror <- mean(diabetes.glm.pr != diabetes.test$Outcome) * 100
glm.testerror
## [1] 23.97959

Using the validation set approach, we have a 23.9795918% test error rate.

# Calculate accuracy of model
correct_predictions <- sum(table(diabetes.glm.pr, diabetes$Outcome[-train])[c(1, 4)])
total <- length(diabetes$Outcome[-train])
accuracy.glm <- (correct_predictions / total) * 100
accuracy.glm
## [1] 76.02041

The accuracy of the model using a logistic regression model is 76.0204082%.

Model #2: Lasso

Fit the Model

# Prepare for cv.glmnet
x <- model.matrix(Outcome ~ . - 1, data = diabetes) # remove outcome variable with -1
y <- diabetes$Outcome

# Use cross-validation to select lambda
lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(x[train, ], y[train], alpha = 1)

# Create plot
plot(lasso.cv)

The plot shows the cross-validation curve (the red-dotted line), and the upper and lower standard deviation curves along the sequence of log(Lambda) values which are across the X-axis. Mean-squared error (CV error) is on the Y-axis. The selected lambda values are shown through the vertical dotted lines. The values (not log versions) are: 0.0065172 and 0.1165702.

Evaluate Model

# Refit the model using lambda.min
lasso.refit <- glmnet(x[train, ], y[train], alpha = 1, lambda = lasso.cv$lambda.min)
coef(lasso.refit)[,1]
##              (Intercept)              Pregnancies                  Glucose 
##            -1.1423121543             0.0085107474             0.0071588456 
##            BloodPressure            SkinThickness                  Insulin 
##             0.0008578604             0.0011594790            -0.0003266257 
##                      BMI DiabetesPedigreeFunction                      Age 
##             0.0084318912             0.0639313118             0.0054547755

When using the lambda that gives the minimum cross-validation error (found in lasso.cv), no variables are shrunk to 0.

# Predict using the test set & the refit model that uses lambda.min
lasso.cv.pr <- predict(lasso.refit, newx = x[-train, ])

# Assign predicted responses to 0 & assign 1 to predicted responses if the posterior probability is >= 0.5
lasso.cv.pr <- ifelse(lasso.cv.pr >= 0.5, 1, 0)

# Confusion Matrix
table(lasso.cv.pr, y[-train])
##            
## lasso.cv.pr   0   1
##           0 117  36
##           1   8  35
# Compute the validation (test) set error
lasso.cv.pr.error <- mean(lasso.cv.pr != y[-train]) * 100
lasso.cv.pr.error
## [1] 22.44898

Using the validation set approach, we have a 22.4489796% test error rate.

# Calculate accuracy of model
correct_predictions <- sum(table(lasso.cv.pr, y[-train])[c(1, 4)])
total <- length(y[-train])
accuracy.lasso <- (correct_predictions / total) * 100
accuracy.lasso
## [1] 77.55102

The accuracy of the model using Lasso is 77.5510204%.
